[] is false in Python; so are other empty aggregates like () and {}; collection types implemented in Python typically follow the same pattern. Thus:<p><pre><code>  >>> if (): print &quot;tuple&quot;
  >>> if []: print &quot;list&quot;
  >>> if {}: print &quot;dict&quot;
  >>> if set(): print &quot;set&quot;
  >>> if &quot;&quot;: print &quot;string&quot;
  >>> import collections
  >>> if collections.Counter(): print &quot;counter&quot;
  >>> if collections.deque(): print &quot;deque&quot;
  >>> 
</code></pre>
(Observe that none of these prints anything.)
